[16:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right. Next, let\'s go over how you can take a generation from Z image and upscale it to 4K or beyond. I\'m going to go over two main ways you can do this. Now, for the first way, you don\'t need to download any additional models. We\'re'

[16:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically going to modify the standard Z image workflow. This is what I like to call a multipass workflow where basically we want to just generate an image first at low resolution and then'

[17:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ll pass it through Z image again to generate a higher resolution. And then for the second method, this does require you to download an additional upscaler, which is around 16 gigabytes in size, but this method is extremely powerful.'

[17:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s going to add so much more details to your generation, and you can make images in 4K or beyond. First, let\'s go over this multipass method, which only uses the image, and you don\'t need to'

[17:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'download any additional upscalers. So, here I\'m starting with the standard Zimage workflow, which you should be familiar with from the previous lesson. Now here what it\'s doing is it\'s just using Z image to generate an image in one go. What we\'re going to do instead'

[17:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is take this image and plug it through another pass of Z image. This time we\'re going to set the resolution to a higher number. So let\'s figure out how to do this. First of all, I\'m going to hold controll and drag over these nodes and'

[17:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then press Ctrl + C and Ctrl +V to copy and paste this down here. And then afterwards basically we are going to take the output image from this first pass and then feed it to this new K sampler. But before we do that notice'

[18:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that this doesn\'t take in an image input. This takes a latent image input. So what we need to do first is convert this into latent space. So to do that let me double click here and then type in VAE and we need to use this step VAE'

[18:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encode. So let\'s connect this image to here. And actually, let me drag this VAE encode down here. And this also requires a VAE, which we\'ve already loaded up here. So, let me drag this here. And'

[18:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now, we can pass this image through RK sampler. But before we do that, we need to increase the resolution of this image. So, I\'m going to double click anywhere here. And then I\'m going to type upscale. And then I\'m going to choose this one, upscale latent by. And'

[18:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then here is where you can choose, you know, how much you want to increase this image by. Let\'s do like two times. And then here are various algorithms you can choose from. Let me connect this over here. And then finally, we can connect'

[18:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this latent output to our second K sampler. And notice that for these two nodes, we also need to connect these inputs. So for the model here, I need to connect it to the Z image turbo model.'

[19:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then for this positive node, I need to connect this down here, plus also the negative node down here. And that\'s pretty much it. Let\'s try out a generation for the original width and'

[19:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'height. Let\'s try 768x 1024. And then for the seed here, I\'m going to set the seed to 42 and set this to fixed so that you can reproduce this as well.'

[19:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Basically, this allows you to generate the exact same image that I\'m going to show you in a second. If you choose a different seed but keep the same settings, it\'s going to generate a slightly different image. And then for the step count for this initial image,'

[19:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because this is just the first pass, we can decrease the step count to something like six steps to start. All right. So afterwards, it\'s going to generate an image. But then this image is also going to be plugged back into another K sampler. This time this image is going'

[19:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to be resized by two times. And then here it\'s going to generate the second upscaled image also using the Z image model. Now there\'s one last setting we need to adjust here, which is the D noise value. You see this is currently'

[20:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'taking the image from our first pass as a reference to regenerate a new image. And this value determines basically how much of the original image should we ignore. So right now it\'s ignoring 100%'

[20:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is just going to create a completely different image. That\'s not what we\'re trying to do, right? We want to retain actually most of the details of the original image and just upscale it to add more detail. So, let\'s set this to something like.5 so that it\'s'

[20:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to retain like 50% of our original image, but just add more details to that image. And that\'s pretty much it. Let\'s click run. All right. And here\'s what we get. So, again, just to make sure you\'re clear on what this does. So, it first'

[20:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uses the image to generate a smaller image like this, which I\'ve set to 768x 1024. Then, this image is converted back into this latent space. And then I chose to increase the size of this by two'

[21:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times. And then this goes back to Z image to generate another round of this image. And here\'s the result. So again, if I open this up side by side so you can compare. Let me just first zoom in on the original image. You can see the'

[21:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'details of her face are quite blurry as I zoom in. But over here you can see that her face and her hair are a lot sharper. You can clearly make out the details of her skin, the eyebrows and'

[21:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the eyelashes, and her nose and lips. Now, you might be wondering, instead of doing all this mess, couldn\'t you just set the original resolution to, you know, double the size, which is 1536x 2048? Well, let\'s actually also generate'

[21:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an image like this. So, what I\'m going to do is hold control and select all these nodes and bypass them so that it only generates this large image in one pass. And then here, I\'m going to set the step count to nine so that it'

[21:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generates a higher quality image because we\'re just running this through one pass. All right. So, here\'s what we get for one pass if we set the resolution to double. Notice that even though I\'ve set the seed to 42 and fixed, it\'s not the'

[22:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same image as before. And that\'s because I changed the resolution. As soon as I change some other setting, it\'s going to give me a completely different image. But nevertheless, let me open this up and give you a side-by-side comparison'

